The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dust Particles&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Diffusion is the net passive movement of molecules or particles from regions of higher to regions of lower concentration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For diffusion to occur there must be a concentration gradient.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the concentration gradient is dust particles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dissimilarity in the amounts of solutes, particles, or molecules between the two regions will cause them to move between the two regions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/04/F2_Savita_Engineering_27-4-22_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 448px; height: 276px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave mirror&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A mirror that curves inward is called a &lt;strong&gt;concave mirror&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The only kind of mirror that can generate&lt;strong&gt; both virtual and real&lt;/strong&gt; images is the concave mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A concave mirror is a curved mirror in which the inside side of the curve has a reflecting surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Recessed inward and away from the incident light is the reflecting surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Concave mirrors focus light inward to a single point of focus.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A plane mirror &lt;/strong&gt;is a mirror with a reflective surface that is flat, or planar.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A lens&lt;/strong&gt; that redirects a straight light beam from its source into a smaller, more vertical, virtual image is called a concave lens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A convex mirror &lt;/strong&gt;is curved so that the reflected side extends outward in the direction of the light source.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For total internal reflection to take place, the light should travel from a denser to rarer medium.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since glass is denser than water, the total internal reflection will not take place if the light goes from water to glass.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of total internal reflection, the angle of incidence must also exceed the critical angle.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sparkling of diamonds, mirages, etc. are examples of total internal reflection.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Rod cells sense colour&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The iris controls the amount of light entering into the eye: &lt;/strong&gt;This &lt;strong&gt;statement is correct.&lt;/strong&gt; The iris is the colored part of the eye and consists of muscles that can contract or expand. By adjusting the size of the pupil (the black circular opening in the center of the iris), the iris controls the amount of light that enters the eye. In bright light, the iris contracts, making the pupil smaller to reduce the amount of light entering the eye. In dim light, the iris expands, making the pupil larger to allow more light into the eye.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cone cells are sensitive to bright light:&lt;/strong&gt; This &lt;strong&gt;statement is correct. &lt;/strong&gt;Cone cells are one of the two types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of the eye. &lt;strong&gt;They are responsible for color vision and are most sensitive to bright light conditions.&lt;/strong&gt; Cone cells are concentrated in the fovea, the central part of the retina, which is responsible for high-resolution vision and color perception.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rod cells sense color: &lt;/strong&gt;This&lt;strong&gt; statement is incorrect. &lt;/strong&gt;Rod cells are the other type of photoreceptor cells in the retina. They are responsible for vision in dim light or low-light conditions, such as night vision. While&lt;strong&gt; rod cells do not provide color vision, they are highly sensitive to light and allow us to see in low-light environments.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;At the blind spot in the eye, there is no vision: &lt;/strong&gt;This &lt;strong&gt;statement is correct. &lt;/strong&gt;The blind spot in the eye, also known as &lt;strong&gt;the optic disc, &lt;/strong&gt;is the area on the retina where&lt;strong&gt; the optic nerve exits the eye. &lt;/strong&gt;This area lacks photoreceptor cells (both rods and cones), so there are no visual receptors to detect light. As a result, light that falls on the&lt;strong&gt; blind spot cannot be detected,&lt;/strong&gt; and there is no vision in that specific part of the visual field. However, our brain compensates for this blind spot, and we usually do not notice it in our day-to-day activities.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Rayleigh&amp;#39;s law of scattering&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Rayleigh&amp;#39;s law of scattering&lt;/span&gt;, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;intensity of light of wavelength&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;lambda;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;present in the scattered light is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;inversely proportional&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;fourth power of &amp;lambda;,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;provided the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;size of the scattering particles&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;much smaller than &amp;lambda;&lt;/span&gt;. Mathematically,&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\Rightarrow I \propto \frac{1}{\lambda^4 }\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;scattered intensity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;maximum for a shorter wavelength&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/07/F1_P.Y_1.7.20_Pallavi_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 393px; height: 213px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the time of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sunrise and sunset&lt;/span&gt;, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sun is near the horizon&lt;/span&gt;. The rays from the sun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;have to travel a larger part of the atmosphere&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;As the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;wavelength&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;red colour&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is more than that of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;blue colour&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;(&amp;lambda;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;≪&amp;lt; &amp;lambda;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;intensity of scattered light&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\propto\frac{1}{{{\lambda ^4}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;, therefore,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;most of the blue light is scattered away&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Only a red colour, which is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;least scattered&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;enters our eyes&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;appears to come from the sun&lt;/span&gt;. Hence the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sun looks red&lt;/span&gt;, both at the time of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sunrise and sunset&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;red colour of the sun&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;at&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sunset&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sunrise&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is due to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;scattering of sunlight&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
